# Consensus-atomic cutovers

`06-branching.mdc`'s 5-working-day / 10-commit guidance is a defense
against unreviewable PRs accumulating, and the default is that every
substantive change splits to land that way. A small number of PRs
genuinely cannot — specifically, PRs whose work would leave the
chain in a non-canonical state at any intermediate split point,
because validators reach different conclusions about the same
block depending on which subset of the cutover they have applied.

This rule names that exception class so the carve-out is auditable
mechanically against named criteria, not against precedent erosion
("we did it for X, can we do it for Y?"). Per
`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc`'s named-criteria principle, the
test is "does this PR meet criteria 1–4?", not "is this case
analogous to a previous case?"

## Scope

This rule defines when a PR may exceed `06-branching.mdc`'s size
and atomicity guidance. It does not relax any other discipline:
the standard reviewer rigor, commit-message discipline
(`90-commits.mdc`), test-gate requirements, and design-doc-first
ordering (`05-system-thinking.mdc`) all still apply. The
exception modifies only the splitting requirement, and only when
all four criteria below are met.

## When this exception applies

All four criteria must be met. Each is independently testable;
"arguable" does not satisfy a criterion.

1. **Consensus-rule boundary.** The PR changes behavior that all
   correctly-implementing nodes must reproduce byte-identically on
   the same input. Internal refactors that preserve consensus
   behavior do not qualify. Logging changes, RPC formatting
   adjustments, internal cache restructurings, function-name
   renames, and file reorganizations of consensus code that
   preserve the rule do **not** qualify; only changes to the
   rule itself (values, computation, validation logic) do.

2. **Indivisible under flag decomposition.** No PR sequence
   exists such that:

   - PR A introduces the new path behind a flag, default off
     (consensus-safe: all nodes still use the old path);
   - PR B flips the flag default to on after some review window
     (consensus-safe iff all nodes agree on flipping the flag at
     the same height/time, which is itself the consensus event);
   - PR C deletes the old path after all nodes have rolled to
     the new default (consensus-safe: only the new path
     remains).

   If any such decomposition exists and would produce
   consensus-safe intermediates at every commit, the PR splits
   and this exception does not apply. Criterion 2 is met only
   when no flag-flippable decomposition produces consensus-safe
   intermediates — typically because the change is to a
   consensus-rule constant whose value must agree across all
   nodes regardless of which code path they call (e.g., a
   timestamp-validation window, a future-time-limit, a
   difficulty-target denominator). For these, a "flag" does not
   exist in any meaningful sense; both nodes have to agree on
   the same value.

3. **Surface enumerated in advance, with evidence.** The PR
   description contains a grep-result-derived enumeration of
   every consensus-affecting symbol, file, and constant being
   changed. The enumeration is the audit evidence that
   completeness is checkable; "I'll find them as I touch each
   file" does not satisfy this criterion. The grep result is
   pasted into the PR description (or linked to a design-doc
   section that contains it) so the reviewer can verify
   completeness against the diff mechanically.

4. **Disposition documented in PR, with reversibility plan.**
   The PR description:

   - cites this rule by name (`07-consensus-atomic-cutovers.mdc`);
   - lists which of criteria 1–4 are met, one sentence per
     criterion explaining the justification (criterion 4's
     entry is the section itself);
   - includes a **reviewer-map section** distinguishing
     consensus-affecting changes (files X, Y, Z; lines A–B in
     each) from mechanical changes (call-site rewires, no
     logic change) from deletions (files removed wholesale).
     The map lets a reviewer prioritize attention without
     spelunking the diff;
   - includes a **rollback procedure** naming the specific
     files and changes that constitute reversion if consensus
     breaks post-merge. "We'd revert the commit" is not a
     rollback procedure — it's the absence of one. The
     procedure is written in advance so a panicked rollback
     isn't reconstructing it in real time.

## What this exception is not

The criteria above are the test. The justifications below are
**explicitly not** criteria; a PR citing this rule must not be
relying on any of them:

- **Convenience.** "This is easier as one PR" is not a
  criterion. Easier-than-splitting is the default expectation
  that `06-branching.mdc` rejects.
- **Velocity.** "Splitting would slow down the migration" is
  not a criterion. Migrations are slow by design; the discipline
  is what makes them bisectable later.
- **Reviewer bandwidth.** "We'd waste reviewer time on three
  PRs" is not a criterion. The exception trades reviewability
  for atomicity; criterion 4's reviewer-map is the
  compensating discipline, not "skip the reviewer's bandwidth
  cost."
- **Retroactive citation.** A PR that did not cite this rule
  in its initial description **cannot** invoke the exception
  later. The disposition is named at PR open; mid-review
  invocation is reactive scope expansion, which the rule does
  not authorize.

## Compensating discipline when the exception is invoked

The exception is reviewability-cost in exchange for
atomicity-correctness. The discipline that makes the trade
auditable rather than a free pass:

- Criterion 3's grep-anchored enumeration is the
  scope-bounding artifact. A PR that grows beyond the
  enumerated surface during review **loses the exception**
  and must be re-opened against the standard size/atomicity
  guidance — i.e., scope creep within an exception-invoking
  PR is grounds for rejecting the PR, not for re-arguing
  the exception.
- Criterion 4's reviewer-map is the attention-routing
  artifact. The map's accuracy is itself a review item: a
  reviewer who finds substantive consensus changes outside
  the map's "consensus-affecting" subsection has identified
  a map-failure, which is grounds for rejecting the PR.
- The rollback procedure is the post-merge safety net. If
  consensus breaks post-merge despite the named criteria,
  the rollback procedure is the runbook. Its existence at
  PR-open is the difference between a panicked revert and
  a procedural revert.

## History of application

The exception class is auditable by enumeration of past
invocations. Each invocation cites this rule, demonstrates
the four criteria are met, and links here. Approved
invocations:

- **LWMA-1 Phase 4** (`docs/design/DAA_LWMA1_PLAN.md` Phase 4).
  Difficulty-algorithm cutover from CryptoNote
  cut-windowed-average to LWMA-1, paired with FTL/MTP value
  changes. The FTL (`7200 → 540`) and MTP (`60 → 11`) value
  changes are consensus-rule constants that no flag-flippable
  decomposition can stage: both validating nodes have to
  agree on the same FTL and MTP values at the same height,
  and a flag-flippable intermediate where some nodes use
  FTL=7200 + LWMA-1 while others use FTL=540 + LWMA-1 is not
  a defensible consensus configuration. Criteria 1
  (consensus-rule boundary: yes, FTL/MTP/algorithm), 2
  (indivisible under flag decomposition: yes, paired
  constants and algorithm), 3 (enumerated in advance:
  `DAA_LWMA1.md` §§9.4–9.7), and 4 (disposition: the Phase
  4 PR description cites this rule). Approved as the first
  instance per Phase 0 review.

Cases evaluated and **not** approved as instances:

- **RandomX v2 Phase 3** (`docs/design/RANDOMX_V2_PLAN.md`).
  The algorithm-body cutover is flag-decomposable per the
  3a/3b/3c plan: Phase 3a adds the FFI swap behind a flag
  default-on while the legacy path remains buildable for the
  3a review window; Phase 3b removes the flag and finishes
  the rewire; Phase 3c performs the implementation deletions.
  Each sub-PR plausibly fits the 5-day / 10-commit ceiling.
  Criterion 2 is not met (flag-flippable decomposition
  exists); the exception does not apply, and RandomX v2
  Phase 3 splits per `06-branching.mdc`.

Future invocations append to this section as part of the PR
itself, not after-the-fact.

## Related rules

- **`00-mission.mdc`** — security and quantum resilience are
  preconditions. The exception exists because consensus
  integrity is the security property that flag-decomposable
  splits are designed to preserve in the normal case;
  consensus-atomic cutovers are the cases where atomicity is
  the property and splittability would undermine it.
- **`05-system-thinking.mdc`** — specification first. The
  surface enumerated in advance (criterion 3) is the
  specification-side artifact that the exception requires; an
  unspecified-in-advance PR is not eligible regardless of
  consensus-atomicity.
- **`06-branching.mdc`** — the rule this exception modifies.
  All other branching guidance (no direct commits to `main`,
  no long-lived feature branches, no `dev`-merges-into-feature
  rebases, no force-pushes to `main`/`dev`) is unmodified.
  The exception touches only the 5-day / 10-commit splitting
  guidance.
- **`15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`** — "while we're here" is the
  enemy. The exception is not authorization for unrelated
  changes to ride along with a consensus-atomic cutover;
  scope is the criterion-3-enumerated surface, and "while
  we're here" additions break the exception per criterion 3.
- **`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc`** — named-criteria
  principle. The exception's auditability comes from the
  named criteria being mechanically testable, the same
  shape that reversion clauses use for "reject now, reopen
  if X." The exception is the same discipline applied to
  "allow this exception only if conditions 1–4."
- **`90-commits.mdc`** — scope per commit. The exception
  relaxes the *PR* splitting guidance; within the PR,
  commits still respect single-purpose scope per the commit
  rule. A consensus-atomic cutover that is one PR is still
  many commits, each with its own bounded scope.
